Classification and regression with linear SVM-s

The aim of this lab is to learn to use maximal margin linear classifiers, support vector classifiers and \(\varepsilon\)-insensitive linear regression.

R packages we use in the lab

We are going to use tidymodels framework and kernlab package.

Datasets of the lab

We are going to use iris and Heart dataset (first is loaded into R by default, the second one is available from Moodle) for classification.

Linear support vector classifier

There are different packages which can be used for fitting support vector methods to data. We are going to consider the package kernlab (an universal package for SVMs). Alternatives are LiblineaR (linear svm-s),e1071 and klaR package which use different computational engines (and may be more efficient in certain situations).

There are different but mathematically equivalent ways to specify the same problem of finding a classifier which reduces to the maximal margin classifier in the case of separable classes. The difference is in the meaning of the penalty term. We consider the formulation where penalty \(C\) denotes the coefficient of the cost of the value of the underlying function to be less then 1 for observations in the class 1 (\(C\) is multiplied by the amount the value is smaller than 1) or greater than -1 in the case of observations from class -1. An alternative is to formulate problem with parameter \(\nu\) which is always between 0 and 1 and is related to the proportion of observations taken into account when determining the classification boundary (proportion of support vectors). More detailed information is available from various text books, and overview is also given in http://is.tuebingen.mpg.de/fileadmin/user_upload/files/publications/pdf3353.pdf

As the coefficients of a given linear function depend on units of measurement and the values of coefficients are important in support vector classification, the results can be quite different for normalized and unnormalized data. Usually it is a good idea to scale the data. The function ksvm from the kernlab package scales both predictors and in the case of regression also response by default.

Linear SVM models are fitted in the tidymodels framework by specifying the model with svm_linear and in order to use kernlab package for fitting, the engine should also be indicated by engine="kernlab".

Exercise 2

Add a variable setose with values Yes and No (according to the value of the Species variable) to iris dataset, name the modified dataset to ex1_data. Use tidymodels framework to fit SVM models to setosa using Sepal.Length and Petal.Length as predictors, using cost values 0.1,1,10 and produce corresponding classification plots with kernlab::plot(extract_fit_engine(model),data=ex1_data) command. What can you say about how cost parameter influences the number of support vectors?

katse <- iris|>mutate(y=if_else(Species=="setosa","Yes","No"))
rec =recipe(y~Petal.Length+Sepal.Length,data=katse)
wf=workflow()|>add_recipe(rec)|>add_model(svm_linear(mode="classification",engine="kernlab",cost=10))
wf_fitted =wf|>fit(katse)
##  Setting default kernel parameters
kernlab::plot(extract_fit_engine(wf_fitted),data=katse)

Exercise 3

Use tuning to find the best linear support vector classifier for AHD in the case of Heart data both for unscaled and scaled predictors by using kernlab engine. Fit the best model to the full Heart data set and produce a graph with respect to variables Chol and MaxHR, which shows observations, actual value of AHD by shape and predicted value of AHD by color.

#scaled, kernlab
wf2.1_tune=workflow()|>add_recipe(rec1)|>add_model(svm_linear(mode="classification",cost=tune(),engine="kernlab"))
Cgrid=data.frame(cost=10^seq(-3,3,length.out=5))
res2.1_tune=tune_grid(wf2.1_tune,cv1,grid=Cgrid,metrics=metric_set(accuracy))
show_best(res2.1_tune,metric="accuracy")
wf2.2_tune=workflow()|>add_recipe(rec1)|>add_model(svm_linear(mode="classification",cost=tune())|>set_engine("kernlab",scaled=FALSE))
Cgrid=data.frame(cost=10^seq(-3,3,length.out=5))
res2.2_tune=tune_grid(wf2.2_tune,cv1,grid=Cgrid,metrics=metric_set(accuracy))
show_best(res2.2_tune,n=5)
## Warning in show_best(res2.2_tune, n = 5): No value of `metric` was given;
## "accuracy" will be used.
wf2.1_fitted=finalize_workflow(wf2.1_tune,select_best(res2.1_tune,metric="accuracy"))|>fit(Heart)
##  Setting default kernel parameters
ggplot(augment(wf2.1_fitted,new_data=Heart))+geom_point(aes(x=Chol,y=MaxHR,shape=AHD,color=.pred_class))

Exercise 4

set.seed(20241128)
splitted=mc_cv(Heart,prop=0.7,strata=AHD,times=1)

test=testing(splitted$splits[[1]])
ggplot(train)+geom_point(aes(x=Chol,y=MaxHR,color=AHD))

Cgrid=data.frame(cost=10^seq(-3,3,length.out=10))
res4_tune=tune_grid(wf4_tune,splitted,grid=Cgrid,metrics=metric_set(accuracy))
show_best(res4_tune,metric="accuracy")
wf4=wf4_tune|>finalize_workflow(select_best(res4_tune,metric="accuracy"))
m4=wf4|>fit(train)
##  Setting default kernel parameters
plot(extract_fit_engine(m4),data=train)

ggplot(test|>mutate(pred=predict(m4,test)$.pred_class))+geom_point(aes(MaxHR,Chol,shape=AHD,color=(pred==AHD)))

Polynomial kernel SVM

The function ksvm from kernlab allows to choose between many different kernels. One of the kernels is polynomial kernel \[k(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{z})=(s\,\mathbf{x}\cdot \mathbf{z}+c)^d,\] where \(s\) is the scale parameter, \(c\) is offset and \(d\) is degree of polynomials. The scale and degree parameters can be set through the command svm_poly() (parameters scale_factor and degree)

SVM with radial basis function kernel

The package kernlab uses definition \[k(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{z})=\exp(-\sigma\|\mathbf{x}-\mathbf{z}\|^2),\] so the parameter \(\sigma\) is not the same as standard deviation in the density function of the normal distribution. This parameter (which name is rbf_sigma) can be set with the command svm_rbf(). A reasonable range for the values of it can be found by the command sigest()
